properties.NAME: Whitehead Road
properties.DESC:
Whitehead Road (in it's entirety) is a collector street from Suwanee Dam Road (major collector) and West Broad Street (Sugar Hill downtown center).  The following subdivisions directly access Whitehead Road: Oaks at Lanier, Herbert Bruce, Whitehead Acres, Bromolow Ridge, Sugar Ridge, Oaks Landing, Westbrook Pointe, Silver Springs, West Brooke Place, Summerfield, Abingdon Place, Regency Lake, and Brighton Park.  Additionally, there are several large and undeveloped parcels fronting Whitehead Road for future development.
Additionally, the City has contacted Lewis Cooksey, Gwinnett County Dept. of Transportation, and he is in agreement with this upgrade in classification.
properties.JUST: According to Gwinnett County's Department of Transportation Traffic count, on January 21, 2009, the estimated Average Daily Trips (ADT) was 4,525.  This number has surely grown as the current estimated population of Sugar Hill is over 18,000 citizens.

properties.NAME: Shadburn Avenue
properties.JUST: Shadburn Avenue meets all of the criteria of an Urban Minor Collector as described in the FHWA Functional Classification Manual, 2013 Edition.  It serves both land access and traffic circulation in lower density residential and commercial areas, penetrates a residential neighborhood only for a short distance, distributes and channels trips between West Shadburn Avenue (minor arterial) to Shadburn Ferry Road (minor arterial) for a length of 1.25 miles and has operating characteristics which include lower speeds and no signalized intersections.  Shadburn Avenue collects traffic from the adjacent residential areas from the north and routes it to the City of Buford Historic Downtown business district.  There are three gateway streets feeding Shadburn Avenue (W Shadburn Ave - Minor Arterial, Little Mill Road - Major Collector, Shadburn Ferry Rd - Minor Arterial) into downtown Buford from Peachtree Industrial Boulevard (Principal Arterial).  Traffic volume also increases along Shadburn Avenue when the adjacent Norfolk Southern railway is active and traffic is unable to cross the railroad tracks to access Main Street (Minor Arterial) which also runs parallel to the railway.
properties.DESC: AADT from GDOT STARS not available.  Existing traffic generator includes residential areas and three gateway streets (W Shadburn Ave - Minor Arterial, Little Mill Road - Major Collector, Shadburn Ferry Rd - Minor Arterial) into downtown Buford from Peachtree Industrial Boulevard (Principal Arterial).

properties.NAME: Moreno Street
properties.JUST: Moreno Street meets all of the criteria of an Urban Minor Collector as described in the FHWA Functional Classification Manual, 2013 Edition.  It serves both land access and traffic circulation in lower density residential and commercial areas, penetrates a residential neighborhood only for a short distance, distributes and channels trips between West Main Street (minor arterial) to East Main Street (minor arterial) for a length of 0.93 miles and has operating characteristics which include lower speeds and few signalized intersections.  The high traffic volumes generated by the Historic Downtown Buford business district along Main Street (parallel Minor Arterial) has re-routed traffic to Moreno Street resulting in an increase in traffic volumes.  Moreno Street connects two Minor Arterial segments and intersects South Lee Street (Minor Arterial) and South Hill Street (Major Collector).
properties.DESC: AADT from GDOT STARS not available.  Existing traffic generator includes the Historic Downtown Buford business district.

properties.NAME: Garnett Street
properties.DESC: AADT from GDOT STARS not available.  Traffic generators include adjacent City of Buford Community Center, Historic Downtown Buford.
properties.JUST: Garnett Street meets all of the criteria of an Urban Minor Collector as described in the FHWA Functional Classification Manual, 2013 Edition.  It serves both land access and traffic circulation in lower density residential and commercial areas, penetrates a residential neighborhood only for a short distance, distributes and channels trips between Buford Highway (minor arterial) to Main Street (minor arterial) for a length of 0.74 miles and has operating characteristics which include lower speeds and no signalized intersections.  There has been a dramatic increase in traffic volume with the recent construction of the adjacent City of Buford Community Center.
